WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Okay. One and action.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Today is Saturday March 9, 2013. My name is Dr. Hasan Kwame Jeffries of the Ohio State University and the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:47.000
I'm with videographer Pete Daniel in Albany, Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:54.000
We are here with Mr. Sam Mahon. Thank you so much for being here with us.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:01.000
I want to begin simply by asking you when and where were you born?

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.000
It was born in Americus, Georgia which is Sumter County, Southwest Georgia.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And what year? Was it the date of birth? 1945.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
1945. So the war is over.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Some people say that World War II usher in this sort of new era of transformation and democracy. What was America's light when you were growing up?

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:42.000
I imagine it was like most small southern rural cities in that the lines of separation were very, very vivid, very stark.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:55.000
As a child growing up, you tended to try to enjoy your childhood but there were instances where you just knew that things just were not right.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And a lot of that came about when you would look at your parents and see how they reacted to situations when white people were present.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:20.000
You notice little subtle things like you look at your father and your mother and you notice how there's virtually no eye contact when they are talking and speaking with white people.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Your father is always looking in a downward manner. Is it that eye contact with somehow create a confrontation?

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:43.000
You notice other things like how your community for instance, the old saying about across the railroad tracks was very true.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:03:01.000
No sidewalks, the roads were dirt at that time, no pavement anywhere. I grew up with an outdoor toilet. We had an outdoor toilet. We didn't get plumbing until I was a senior in high school.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:18.000
My mother was a domestic worker. She worked in white people's home. That's what she did as employment. My father was a factory worker who worked in a basket factory that produced baskets to contain (the) fruit, large shipments of fruit.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
But what were their names?

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:28.000
My father's name was Bergen Mahon. My mother's name was Lula Bell. My maiden name was Walker.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:37.000
I was a seventh of six children. I was a sixth. I had a sister that younger than myself.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Other things that you pick up on like for instance, when you're totally dependent on white stuff for their services, for instance, there was always the...

00:03:52.000 --> 00:04:02.000
There was what we call the policy man, the insurance agent who would come to do it or do other industries to collect the money for the policies.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:09.000
They would simply come up to your house and not even knock and just simply walk into your house. That's how white agents.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:16.000
That's how much they took liberty. That's how much they went control.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So of your everyday existence you saw these things. But it didn't really manage best in terms of you as a child, you know you accepted these things.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:36.000
And of course, anytime you left the house your parents would always tell you, you knew your place, you knew what you could do and what you couldn't do.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And it was out of fear for your life that they did these things. So you grew up under those circumstances.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But I have to say that even though you internalize these things, it was something that you didn't really resist. You went along with it.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:10.000
It was only until I became engaged in what was called. There was a group of ministers who would start a voter registration project called the Americus Voters League.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:17.000
This was prior to any civil rights organizations coming to America. And I was probably in the 10th grade or something like that.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And began to work in terms of trying to talk to other students about voter registration and those kinds of things.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
To you about 16? Yeah, about 1916-1961.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Exactly. And these are students in your high school? Yeah, exactly. And what did you go to school?

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:57.000
I graduated some of the county high school in Americus, Georgia. I went through the entire school system there and went from schools that had the old pot-bellied pot-bellied wood stoves and until finally getting air-conditioned schools when I finally graduated from school.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:06.000
So you become involved with this voter league? Yeah. And what led you to become involved with them?

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:16.000
I think it was more out of having something to do, I think. In fact, that's what led me to become more of an activist later on.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:26.000
It was in a small town. You had very little outlets in terms of trying to do things that were outside of the norm.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And so anything that had a sense of being something different or then I was attracted to that.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:43.000
How did your classmates respond to you when you start talking to them about some of the things that you're doing with the voter league?

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Well, some of them responded quite positively. And then those that did took it as a challenge.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And there was a very short time between that time and when SNCC came into the records. And so that further galvanized those people who had been receptive in the first place.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And so it was at that time that we sort of moved from that right into that activism within the movement, which later became America's movement.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Did your parents, what did they think about your early involvement, even before Snick gets there?

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:35.000
My parents were mainly disengaged. And I think a lot of it had to do. My father was a working man. He had very little conversation and he just worked.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:46.000
My mom, as a domestic, was more receptive to conversation. She had no particular feelings about it.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:55.000
But there was very little conversation in terms of what I was doing in terms of that kind of work and what happened.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:17.000
But they were not against it. They were very supportive. And what I did, they were of course always fearful. But especially my father, who, but my mother was, she had fears also, but she was more likely to pull along with the things that I was doing at that time.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
How about your siblings?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:28.000
By that time, all the siblings were away from home. During this time, it was myself and my younger sister, who was three years younger.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And of course, she was not involved because she got pregnant before she finished school and moved away to Florida and started a family.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:52.000
And so I was virtually left there, all my older brothers had joined the military, we're in service. And so there was very little interaction between me and my other siblings at that time.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:09:04.000
In fact, many of them know that I was involved in this until years later. I mean, they just didn't pay attention to what the things that was happening at my time.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:14.000
So in this interim period between you start and you get your feet wet, you're beginning to become sort of publicly active.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And so are there other things that you're doing as well with the voters lead before you encounter a SNCC folk?

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:30.000
No, not at all. Just really going to school and trying to manipulate through that, some things that kids normally do in that period.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:46.000
I worked outside jobs, I picked cotton. Before school opened up, I pulled up peanuts, I picked peaches, you know, you name it in field work.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.000
And then also as a student in school, I got a job working at a clothing store, cleaning up and what have you.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So I did the normal things that kids do at that time. If you can get a job, you know, then that's where I did.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:08.000
What was some of, or when did you become engaged with SNCC?

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Stick came into America's in late 1962. Don Harris, John Perdew, Ralph Allen, I believe, the first work to came in.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:31.000
They were dispatched there from here, from Albany, by a project director, Charles Sherrod.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And at the time they were expanding their work in several counties around throughout the southern border area.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:49.000
America was chosen because of the demographics and the dynamics there. And most of these rural counties blacks comprised full of 50% of the population.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:11:00.000
median income was about $1200 a year for blacks, you know, and it was maybe tripled that for white school, four or five times after white school.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:08.000
Schools of course were a second class. I never got a new book at all throughout the 12 years of school.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:18.000
We always had books passed on to us. We knew that, you know how you got a book in school in the next class and you'd have all these names written into the books, you know.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:25.000
So we knew as students that we were two or three years behind in terms of the books that we received.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:35.000
But we had not your teachers at that time who cared for us. And we did the best they could with what they had.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:45.000
And so we we cherish that. To the state we cherish that because they laid the ground was first to do the work that I feel that I began doing later on.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:54.000
You're still in high school at the time. What do you think about these freedom writers that so many people call them?

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:02.000
As I said, anything that was new to a kid, one of the smaller town was exciting, interesting.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:13.000
They came into America's. They had Northern dialects, you know, they were from college campuses. They bought books with them. Books that I had never seen before.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:31.000
They set up what was called a SNCC house where they moved into these houses and immediately began to reach out to students and the pastors and ministers really could to begin to try and build workers to work on voter registration.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So the SNCC house became a hangout house for kids, you know, we would go there and we began doing things like printing leaflets and flyers on the old mimeograph machines and hand-crank machines.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:13:14.000
And the fact that they introduced us to black authors, you know, Richard Wright, James Baldwin, you know, the boy and all these people that we hadn't heard of gave us a whole sense of meaning, you know, and being, you know, and as a kid, it really, it really sparked an interest in us and made us want to come back to that house every day after school.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:21.000
You know, see what they had to do, they wanted us to do for them, you know, so that's literally how it started, you know.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And what, what, what was the freedom house?

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:32.000
It would be a rental house, an old wood frame house, shotgun house that some might have read to them, you know, for little nothing.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:41.000
It may have made out of head running water, you know, but it was just a meeting house and they slept there sometimes on the floor, sleeping bags, what happened, you know.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And so I even wound up spending the night there, you know, just hanging out at the SNCC house.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:53.000
And that's how my activism began.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:14:10.000
And the more I stayed there, the more my interest increased. And the more I recognized the duality of this system that we lived in, and that there was a chance it was up in the batter.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:16.000
How did you get involved with the protest that the movie did?

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:26.000
We spent several months working on voter registration. We would canvas door to door through advocacy, and not only in the city, but we went out to the counties also.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
And this is an anniversary.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Is it an anniversary for this? 63?

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Yes, okay.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:54.000
We recognized, and through SNCC made us recognize that the only way to form the power, the change in the dynamics of the system, was through getting people registered, choosing our own candidates, looking them to office, who would look after our own interests before change.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:05.000
So it was going to be a time to recognize that voting was power. And so we spent our days, and even as a record on voter registration, we would go to the house to house.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
We would take down names.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.000
We would schedule times, and we could come back and pick them up to take them down the register.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:23.000
We set up Freedom School, because we were talking about people who some who could not read or write, some who had mostly had never voted.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And so the Freedom Houses were places where we would organize, and teach people how to read and write, or at least pass the exams, the literacy test at that time.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:47.000
It was a place of organizing, strategy, and what have you, what neighborhoods we would canvas, who would drive the cars to take them down.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:58.000
It was also a place where we would taught each other, self defense techniques, not fighting back because we had accepted the principle of nonviolence.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:10.000
But basically teaching us how to protect ourselves, and we were attacked, if we were attacked, how to curl up in a fetal position if you were beaten and kicked and what have you.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:24.000
We would go through these scenarios of how if someone spat in your face, you know, how would you respond, and just prepare us for what we knew eventually was going to come.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
And that they came?

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:38.000
That they came, we eventually moved from voter registration to begin and to test the laws of public accommodation.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And strange enough, this didn't come from stick workers, it came from the students themselves.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
The young people, the young people.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
You and your friends?

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
Yes.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Who said, we wanted to go to these places, you know, that had bought us, you know, discriminated against us.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:06.000
The main theory was the most visible place downtown. It was a place, and it was both, when I say visible, the interests were so stark, the differences.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:14.000
The black interest was, you had to walk around the side of the theater down a dark alley, about 150 feet.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:21.000
You woke up three fights of stairs and sitting about going to look at the theater.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So one night, 11 of us decided we were going to go to the front, entrusted to try to purchase tickets.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
We stood there for about a half an hour and they wouldn't sell us tickets.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
So we just stood there and then the police came finally.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:42.000
And they asked us to disperse, we did not disperse the air, sitting with charge with this disorderly conduct and fighting an officer.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And it took us on a paddy wagon, took us off the jail.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:18:00.000
The next morning we went to Kuwait and they released us on probation, which was a 90 day probation.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:07.000
And being kids, we didn't realize that if you got arrested again, you couldn't be bailed out.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:13.000
And nobody took the time to explain to us that because one week later, I was arrested again.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:19.000
And all of us from the original group, from the original 11 were arrested again.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
And as a part of another demonstration.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
And at the same theater.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:37.000
And immediately they singled us out the four of us who had previously arrested and they sent us to prison, to the Sumter County prison farm.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:44.000
So you get arrested, you spend the night in jail, they pull you out immediately.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
They put us in jail.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
The next one we go back to court.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Same judge.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Same judge.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:55.000
And they tell us that we have to immediately begin those sentences.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:03.000
So at some point you realize, wait a minute, I'm about to do some time.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.000
Yeah, exactly.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.000
What are you thinking?

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:11.000
Well, we still been grasped that we wouldn't have to do this time.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:19.000
We just felt as kids that somehow we were going to get out of this because there were two girls, two boys and two girls.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And so it happened overnight.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
This is literally what they put us on the streets.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Well, the first day they took us, they put us in prison and took us out to do road work.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.000
Cutting grasses and cutting grass and things like that.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Well, the local ministers went to City Hall and demanded, which was really something at its time, that they not put the women on the street, the girls on the streets.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:54.000
So they did not.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:04.000
My friend and I, the other guy, we decided to, we just sat down and sat and were not going to work.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:12.000
So when we did that, they took the two of us down to the county jail, for the city of the county jail.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:32.000
We put us in the Hole, which was about a four by six foot concrete enclosure, with a little sit at the bottom about 46 inches wide, where they would each day put in a piece of bread and a cup of water.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:37.000
Well, we decided we weren't going to eat them on a hunger strike.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So we're total darkness for about seven days.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:48.000
We did, we fasted for about seven days until we passed out.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:53.000
Now, when you, in close proximity, was the other hole, were you together or were you accepting?

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:56.000
We got in the same hole.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:06.000
And so they took us out of the hole and we were just literally passed out.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:17.000
They took us to the hospital and filled us with some fluids and then we went back to the jail and we went back to work.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
We went to work two days after that.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:29.000
And the jobs that we did, ran some cutting grass on the side of the streets, picking up garbage on weekends.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:36.000
The worst job was cleaning out the city switch.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
They saved that specially for us.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:43.000
None of the other prisoners had to do this, who were in all kinds of crimes, right?

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:47.000
You think these switch treatment plants, where they had these long pools?

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.000
Well, America's had three of them. I believe it was three.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:57.000
And they would take us there with an armed guard.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And there was a dump truck that found us and it gave us two shovels.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And it cost all day to shovel out these pools of raw sewage, of sewage at the treatment plants.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:17.000
I believe we did that maybe once a week, twice a week.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:22.000
Maybe twice a week, yeah, twice a week, I believe something like that.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.000
But that was very specifically for us because we were those no good-adgettakers.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:32.000
And this is three months. I mean, you got 90 days, you're young.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:39.000
You do. Your parents, they must be, you obviously worried.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
What did they say?

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:48.000
Of course, my father was most visibly upset.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:53.000
My mother was also upset. My father was just angry, I think.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:23:00.000
As I said before, he never really, he was just fearful of my life.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:08.000
And the fact that I had kind of disobeyed him and that you got in and got yourself in the trouble really now.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:16.000
But they stood by me, they supported me, especially my mom.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
She would bring things to her.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:25.000
And then working on the street was different than other people who were just jailed.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
I mean, no people, we're just incarcerated all the time.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:35.000
So working on the street gave us an opportunity to have people pass us by to come by and they would see us working on the street.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
And they would let us know what's going on in the movement.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:45.000
They would give us money sometimes by things like that.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:49.000
I started smoking cigarettes, cigarettes, cigarettes, things like that at that time.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Unfortunately, yeah, I was smoking.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:56.000
But it was in kind of doing an outlet for us to get information.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.000
It's the kind of freedom we get on the outside.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
We would work all day long.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:05.000
And in the day, they'd bring us back to the jail, say, don't lock us up at night.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:12.000
And at night, we would watch other people who were arrested on the day being brought in.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:22.000
And to see other people continuing to fight and to continue to demonstrate gave us really that's what got us through.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:27.000
How did the jailer's treacher?

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:36.000
Well, the jailers were very racist, very, very cold, very...

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:42.000
Just no sympathy at all for what we were doing.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:50.000
The sheriff of something kind with that time was the sheriff's chapel, where the whole was, where the best way they kept us in the whole.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:57.000
He was the one who wanted (Dr.) King to refer to as a meanest man in the world after the king was jailed in this jail in 1961.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Had a reputation for just really beating up blacks for little or nothing.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.000
And that was really the local police department at that time.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:14.000
Just some very racist police department.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:18.000
And had no tolerance for what we were doing at that time at all.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
And what was the sheriff's name again?

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:25.000
Sheriff Fred Chappell.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:29.000
He was probably...

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:33.000
I'm totally was the biggest bootlegger in the county as well.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:43.000
But you could compare them to Jim Clark, Al Lingo, but Sheriff Fred Chappell was his name.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:49.000
And how about the other inmates, those who weren't in for movement, activism?

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
How did they respond to you?

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:54.000
They responded very positively.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:03.000
They were mostly older guys who oftentimes prays us for what we were doing.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:08.000
And kind of acted as big brothers to us, you know, protected us.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:15.000
If there was someone who wanted to harm us, you know, then they were quite, quite receptive to us.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
And we looked upon them as...

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:22.000
And we were always about trying to enlighten them as well while we were in there.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:30.000
We think that was an opportunity to bring them into the fold, you know, and to talk about the conditions on which they got the end of the first place.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
To do some organizing.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
Exactly.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:36.000
A great place to organize.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
It's a matter of fact.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
You have a cap of bodies.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Exactly.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
So you do your time.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.000
You survive.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:45.000
Yes.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
You make it through.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
What do you remember coming out?

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
Do you remember being released?

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.000
I do.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:57.000
And no fanfare.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:58.000
We were just simply released.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:01.000
We did our time when we got out.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:08.000
And but that's when I was even more committed to doing this work.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:09.000
I began to...

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:12.000
That's when I...

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
I finished high school.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
And then immediately after that I joined Stiggy.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And began to continue working throughout America.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
But I also worked in other counties around the counties as well.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
Continue doing voter registration.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.000
Continue doing...

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Testing the laws of the public, the combination of what have you.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:39.000
I remember the night the Civil Rights Bill was signed.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:43.000
We decided we were going to test it at a local restaurant.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
This is July 64.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:46.000
Exactly.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
Yeah.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:54.000
Myself and John Perdew, who I believe is here, who was one of the Americans for.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
SNCC worker.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:02.000
Bob Mants, out of Morehouse, who we've seen passed away.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:09.000
And for the students, we went down to a place called the Hasty House restaurant.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And we sat there and we ordered...

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.000
We tried to order the food but the waiters never came.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
One of us, one of the guys who we...

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:23.000
With us decided that he needed to go to the restroom.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
And the restroom was outside.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:29.000
He had to go outside and go around to the side of the building.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:33.000
While we were waiting, no one came to take our order.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:38.000
But about 10 minutes passed, we noticed that he hadn't come back from the restroom.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:44.000
So we finally got up and sat to get up and leave.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
And as we get up to leave to go to the car,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:52.000
we met by a group of whites who would come across the street from a service station with tire irons.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
And they had a lot of tire arms and...

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
And baseball bats.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
And so they waited until we got into the car,

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:04.000
which was a convertible car.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:10.000
And then they just ran out on the car with baseball bats and tires and beat us on top of our heads.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:14.000
And we finally got the car started and we just...

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
We get out of there.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.000
Without the guy who had gone to the restroom.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.000
We talked about two days later.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:27.000
And he said what happened was that when he went to the restroom, he was attacked.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:28.000
And beaten.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:31.000
And he just ran off and never came back.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.000
And so...

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.000
But that was the first...

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:42.000
Even we decided to test the laws of public accommodation.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
The Americas for.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.000
This happens after...

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
And this was...

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.000
The Americas for was...

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:56.000
Before that, this was 63 years.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.000
There was a demonstration.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:05.000
In fact, again,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:14.000
Slickhead felt that night demonstrations were really dangerous.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.000
And sort of encouraged it not to do it.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:20.000
But again, students took the lead.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:22.000
And on this particular night,

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
they marched from the church where we had a mass meeting and was going downtown.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
To demonstrate.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
And as it happened, the workers,

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.000
St. Rookers were also downtown.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And that night, they unleashed dogs and water hoses on the demonstrators.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:46.000
And people were arrested.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:49.000
And they...

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
they keyed in on the SNCC workers.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:54.000
And Don Harris, John Purdue,

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:58.000
there was a core worker, Zev Aelony.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:02.000
And the four of them was Ralph Allen also from SNCC.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.000
And charging with a century-old sedition law,

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:10.000
which carried the death penalty.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:17.000
They stayed in jail, I believe, for about 84 days,

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
85 days.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And were finally released by a three-judge (federal) panel.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:26.000
The significance of that...

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.000
If the state had prevailed on those charges,

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:32.000
it would have stifled movements all around the country.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
Because it meant that the police had the right to detain,

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:39.000
arrested detained workers without cause.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:42.000
And put them in jail.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:49.000
And so the legal team was a team that included C.B. King of Albany.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:52.000
Donald Hollowell, like Atlanta,

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:55.000
Constance Baker, Martin Lee, was on the team.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
Another lawyer out of Macon, Georgia,

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:01.000
I believe Larry Thompson, I believe, was his name.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:05.000
And they won that case.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.000
So it was very significant in that they prevailed.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:18.000
And it provided even more strength for people to move forward in the movement.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:26.000
Would you remember hearing about them possibly facing execution?

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:31.000
That possibility was always on people's mind.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Because we knew that the power structure as it was was determined to do all in its power

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:41.000
to curtail any movement activity.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:45.000
And so that possibility never left us.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:49.000
But we just felt confident that people were not going to let this go.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:54.000
That people were willing to get onto the streets and protests and demand

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:57.000
that these people be released.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:03.000
We were helpful in getting a nationwide movement

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:11.000
to build groups across the country from college campuses,

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:16.000
legal groups across the country to write letters of protest.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:20.000
There was massive fundraising for that benefit.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And so we were encouraged by the output of that support.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.000
And we knew that the more support we got,

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:32.000
the more that the nation turned its eyes on this particular case

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
that we would be successful.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
So we were confident that they were going to be released at some point.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:42.000
And in the case, the case worked as way all the way to the Supreme Court.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:43.000
Exactly.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:49.000
Do you remember hearing when word came down that the court had upheld the lower court ruling

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:52.000
from not mistaken that Georgia can't do this?

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Exactly.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
Yes. Of course, we were all jubilant.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:02.000
I have photos that we've collected from our collective sense stand of

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:08.000
the jubilant faces as they were released upon their release.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.000
The interesting thing now is that the courthouse where they were tried

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:21.000
is where we now have our display of memorabilia from that movement from that time.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
That's where the welcome center is now.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
It was the fellow courthouse at that time.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.000
Then became a post office and now it's a welcome center.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:34.000
That's an interesting turn around.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:38.000
Certainly when people think about America as they think about the Americas for.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:45.000
But they also think about those young girls who were demonstrating in America's

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:50.000
and then wind up in the Leesburg stockade.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:57.000
Could you tell us how that occurred, what happened there?

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:02.000
As more and more people got into the streets and demonstrated that jails became full.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:07.000
We filled the Americas city jails so they began looking around the county for

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
alternate locations so they could house people.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:20.000
There were several abandoned prison camps that were made available to them.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:26.000
There were people of jail not only We filled the jails in Americus the city jail, the county jails.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:32.000
Then they started taking people out to places like Terrell County.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
People were jailed there.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:40.000
They took people to the Leesburg, Georgia, the Leesburg stockade.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:43.000
I wouldn't make Leesburg significant with that.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
Leesburg's where the juvenile girls were taken.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
Those under 16 years of age.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.000
It was an abandoned prison camp.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:02.000
No bedding, all concrete, no shower facilities.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:08.000
One toilet for some 35 to 40 young girls.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:17.000
On one occasion one of the guards threw a rattlesnake into the whole den area.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:30.000
They began screaming and one of the guards came and said, you know, pretended that he didn't know that there was no stake in there.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:38.000
Then one of the guards let all the girls out so they could look for the snakes supposedly.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:44.000
As it turned out one of the guards went and found the state and picked it up.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:50.000
We were told later on by some of the girls who were housed in there.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:56.000
This guy picked the stink up like he knew it was his pet.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:03.000
There were times when there were white men who would drive up to the jail.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
They knew they were housed there.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:09.000
They would try to get the guards to convince them to let them go inside and have what they say.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:12.000
Have some fun with the girls.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:16.000
Young girls.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:28.000
It was a classic case of the inhumanity that these people were willing to place on young girls.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.000
And Lee's Brooks located could have known that.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:43.000
So much so that people like SS Magazine did a story on it a few years ago on that episode.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:50.000
They would call the stolen girls because the way they wanted the police burst in the middle of the night

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:56.000
the police brought a tractor trailer up to the jail.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:03.000
And one by one they were hooded into the back of the tractor trailer in the middle of the night and taken to this place in the dark.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.000
They had no idea where they were going.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:16.000
And it was days later, maybe more than a week later, that the parents knew they didn't know where they were.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Nobody knew where they were.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:23.000
So that's why the stolen girls were given to them.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And so that's what made the story even more compelling and more significant.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:32.000
That they would do this to young juveniles.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:38.000
And that was the real significance of that particular hold in place.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.000
Were you all looking for them?

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
I mean, you all didn't know where they were either.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.000
Well, I was in constant, I was in jail at the time myself.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:52.000
But of course, parents were trying to get information.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:58.000
And eventually they found out what they were doing and what happened.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:03.000
But they literally didn't know what they were until later on.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:10.000
In addition to the direct action work, the citizens and the demonstrations,

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:14.000
you also do a voter registration work.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:23.000
And canvassing and the life where there are other activities as well that you work specifically involved in with SNCC during that time.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:28.000
So 64 and moving into 65.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:33.000
It's all about organizing.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:44.000
There wasn't a time when President domestic workers were being threatened,

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:53.000
if any of that children were involved in any movement activity, some were fired.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:40:04.000
And so we began a, along with some of the domestic workers, they formed a Maids Union.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:05.000
What was this?

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:11.000
This was in 6465.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:19.000
And these women got together and decided they wanted to ask for the men better wages,

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:22.000
those who were still employed.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:32.000
And so the first Maze Union was formed by the mother of several of the young girls who had been incarcerated.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:36.000
So we organized things like, we have to organize things like that.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:42.000
We also set up a library because at the time we couldn't use a local library.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:48.000
We organized a national campaign to get schools around the country to donate books to America.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:55.000
At one time we had about 20,000 books thrown into America from places around the country.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:59.000
And we set up our own library, what was called the U-Center here at America's.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:08.000
Before that was called the Colored Hospital back in the 40s and 50s,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
which trained black doctors.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And in fact at one time this particular facility trained more black doctors in any place in the country.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:23.000
In the 40s and 50s that building still stands and it went on the national historic registry,

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:26.000
I believe about four or five years ago.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:31.000
So we continued to do things like that to organize Maze unions.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:35.000
We formed a quilting union of women quilters.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:40.000
And these were all of the people who could support themselves in case they were fried, you know,

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.000
leave their jobs and what have you.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:49.000
And of course, the crux of all this was voter registration and voter registration.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:56.000
We were always trying to mobilize people to run for office.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:05.000
And along with that voter registration was key in terms of getting people registered and getting registered to support those candidates.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:10.000
So it was an ongoing work, but that was really the major focus registered people to vote.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:18.000
In connected with that, I mean there is another case that comes out of America's that has to do with,

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:22.000
I mean at the time although people are trying to register, you still have segregated lines.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:27.000
And the life, could you say a little bit about that?

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:34.000
Mary Kate Bell Fishbel was the first woman to qualify for the Democratic primary in some of the counties.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
She ran for office of Justice of the Peace.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
And what years is this?

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:43.000
This was 1965.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:52.000
On the dearly election, as people were voting, she and three other women,

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:58.000
Mamie Campbell, who was the wife of the America's movement president, Reverend Robert Campbell,

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:04.000
Gloria Wise, who is now deceased and Lena Turner, who lives in Atlantic City,

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:11.000
they decided to try to vote in the white voting line.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:15.000
When they refused to leave, they were all arrested, put in jail.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:26.000
And that led to a daily deluge of demonstrations, protests, demand in their release.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:31.000
These demonstrations went on every day.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:37.000
And during that time there were several confrontations with the police,

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:43.000
several people were beating, throwing in jail.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:46.000
One day the white merchants of the city decided to get together,

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:52.000
and this was about maybe three or four days after they had been arrested.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:56.000
The merchants got together and decided they were going to bond the women out of jail.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:57.000
The white merchants?

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:02.000
The white merchants, because they feared more trouble, more, as they call it,

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:06.000
more confrontation in the streets.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:13.000
So faced with that, the women decided that we're not going to accept it.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:20.000
They wrote a letter which we have and now we now have that letter and I request that we've been keeping.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:24.000
And it says simply that these are the same merchants they've stood by.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:35.000
It's black kids, boys and girls were beaten and assaulted for simply trying to demonstrate

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
their rights.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:43.000
And now you've come forward to bond us out of jail and they cite hypocrisy of them,

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:51.000
not speaking out then, but one debond us out, simply to keep quiet and what have you.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:55.000
So they refused to bond, they stayed in jail.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:01.000
And about a week later they were released, federal judge released them,

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:05.000
unconditionally, dropped the charges and what have you.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:12.000
And declared that segregated voting lines in Sumter,

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
so that was significant.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:21.000
A significant victory that really propelled more people who saw power in their numbers.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:29.000
And so each victory was one that really unified us and swelled the numbers in terms of people

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
willing to get out there and protest.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:45.000
And you were with the America's movement for up and two and through 1966.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:48.000
Yeah, 1966, that's correct.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:52.000
And then you head down to Mississippi to Tougaloo.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:54.000
Head to Mississippi.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:46:00.000
What happened was that SNCC had started a program of providing scholarship money for kids

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:08.000
who weren't you go to school, provided that you come back to your community and do some work,

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
continue doing some work.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:16.000
And so I jumped at the opportunity, I didn't know anything about Tougaloo.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:20.000
I just knew other stick people who were up in Mississippi, you know.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:25.000
Went to Mississippi, went to Tougaloo, had planned the major in social sociology.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:38.000
Got the campus and recognized that Tougaloo was had been at the forefront of a lot of civil rights activity in Mississippi.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:48.000
And at that time, Tougaloo, to my knowledge had the only was the only Black institution [actively] protesting the (war in.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:56.000
And so I joined that movement and became very involved in activities there in Mississippi.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:08.000
Later on went to places like Greenville, working with a sharp opposite what have you, things like that.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
I left there after two years because most of my time I've been spent actually as an activist off campus.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:19.000
It was difficult to really settle in as a student after having gone through what happened in America

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:24.000
and seeing the conditions that in a lot of places simply were not changing.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:27.000
And there was more work to be done.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:33.000
So once you become an activist, you don't settle down anymore, you continue it.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:39.000
And to this day, you know, you want to be in the fight, you know, somehow.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.000
There was no going back.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
No going back, never going back.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.000
And so after you leave Tougaloo, what do you do after that?

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:59.000
I, while it took a little, I met, there was a lawyer who was from America's who had been run out of America

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:06.000
and a white lawyer who was forced to flee America's because he had been sympathetic to the movement.

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.000
His name was Warren Fortson.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:15.000
His brother at the time happened to be Ben Fortson, who was Secretary of State in Atlanta.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:23.000
Well, Forson had, was head of the America School Board at that time, I believe,

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:29.000
and had fought to integrate the library here in America's.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:34.000
The thing that really pushed him over the age and where the white community was the fact that he,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:40.000
there were two students who had been arrested, born a girl.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:45.000
One was the first student, one of the first students to integrate the white high school,

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:49.000
Roberta Freeman, and her boyfriend.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:53.000
They were at Parking one night, as kids, you know.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:59.000
And so the policeman pulled up alongside them and decided to charge them with,

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:04.000
and these were an exposure, fornication, what had he, and arrested them.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:11.000
Now, we feel that this was brought on by the fact that she had integrated in America's high,

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:14.000
and she was doing it gradually.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:20.000
And we feel that they put these charges on them to keep her from being the first black to graduate from America's high.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:28.000
Well, Forson was, he took that case on, and he defended them in court, successfully.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:32.000
But he was never able to live in the city after that.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:37.000
He was hounded by the Ku Klux Klan. His own neighbors turned against him.

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:41.000
People he had gone to church with turned against him.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:45.000
He was afraid to sit by his window at night because of threats.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:48.000
So he has finally moved to Atlanta.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:58.000
And so, fast forward to 67, 68.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:08.000
I'm at a lecture at Tugulu, and Forson happens to be there.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:15.000
And I see him, and we speak to each other, and we connect.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:19.000
And so I tell him that I'm going to be leaving to Luprace and going back to America.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:23.000
So he said, what are you going to do? I said, well, I don't know.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:28.000
So he said, why don't you go back to Atlanta and see my brother?

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:33.000
I'll call my brother and tell him that you're looking for some work.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:41.000
So I get back to Atlanta, and I go to the Secretary of State's office.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:49.000
And he sends me to the Georgia Department of Archives, which is on the Secretary of State's office.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:56.000
And I go in there, and I take a job as an apprentice in paper conservation, restoration.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And I learned the craft, and I wound up standing there for about 15 years.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:06.000
Well, 12 or 15 years, actually.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:15.000
But before I left there, I began to study photography and began to take photographs,

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:18.000
and I opened up an art gallery while I was still working here.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:19.000
Moving in that gallery?

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:22.000
Ancestral Art Gallery.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:33.000
And when I felt comfortable enough, I resigned the job and I left and did the gallery full time.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:40.000
And I think being in the movement prepared me for that, because I'd always been intrigued by images.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:51.000
And of course being in the movement, a lot of times it was only images that propelled people, signs that were made, photographs that were taken.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:57.000
And so I began to do that as a street photographer.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:03.000
And I grew up in the movement of images by other artists as well.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:16.000
But that was a way of continuing that to this and because it allowed me to elevate the work of African American artists who didn't have venues for the most part in places like Atlanta.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:25.000
Whose work was had been diminished by traditional, you know, outbursts, galleries and what have you.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:36.000
And marginalized, you know, so that led me to another form of activism in terms of trying to project the arts more positively than the African American community.

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.000
And it was a place where people could come.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:43.000
It was not just a gallery to buy art, but it was a place where people could come to be informed.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:48.000
We had poetry sessions there.

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:51.000
We had public meetings there.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:56.000
They had to do with things in terms of in the community.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:02.000
So it was an outlet to continue that activism, but in a different, you know, a different way.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:09.000
I want to wrap up in a second by talking about the American movement, remember it.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.000
I want to go back just quickly, just briefly if we can.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:19.000
And ask you about you were working, you were engaged in anti-war protests.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:23.000
But then you were drafted.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:36.000
I was drafted. Yes. In fact, that's, I was never, I was drafted in 69.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:47.000
And when I went into the military, I had basic training at Fort Benning, Georgia, which was hours drive from a hometown.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:55.000
Where most people go on to advance training when you finish basic, they kept me there at Fort Benning.

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
They never gave me a security clearance.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:05.000
And they said it was because of my arrest record in America.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:10.000
So instead of sending me on to an advanced training, they sent me into what was called a hold of a company (?).

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:17.000
And with that meant, with that means is that it's a company where all you do is duty work.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:27.000
You dig ditches, you cut grass, you clean the trees, bathrooms, and what have you for the offices and what have you.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:37.000
It was a place where, during this time, it was common for people who had been gotten arrested during the Vietnam War.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:41.000
They gave you choice of either going to prison or going to the war.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:46.000
So here I was in this group.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:53.000
And they literally woke you up every morning at 6.30 and you had a duties to do.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:56.000
It would be digging ditches, they cut grass.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:04.000
In fact, one of the duties was to build an archery course for the offices, which literally go into this jungle like wood, wooded area.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And dig highways through and cut highways through to dig up and set up these targets.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:12.000
And it was another form of punishment, you know.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:15.000
I did that for a whole year.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:21.000
And at the end of the year, someone decided they were going to close a training camp at Fort Benning.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:24.000
So they closed on a training camp, the center.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:31.000
And so if everybody either got shipped to Vietnam or Germany, I got sent to Germany.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:35.000
I still didn't have a security clearance.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:42.000
They gave me an MOS, they gave me a duty, which was clerk type, is just the name.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:50.000
And so they sent me to Europe to what was called a material command, about a five hour drive from Paris, France.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:58.000
They literally put me in an office behind a big office, but in the back.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.000
But then there's going to cheer.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:04.000
And I sent there all day long.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:10.000
I did nothing.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:14.000
So what I did in my time was that I picked up a camera.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:19.000
That was when I first picked up the camera.

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:25.000
I used my weekends. I bought a car from a guy who was coming back to the States, paid him 100 bucks for a car.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:34.000
And I would take off on weekends, drive to the countryside, drive to Paris, a six hour drive, five hour drive.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:39.000
And I spent all my time doing that.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:42.000
But for the rest of that, my service time.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:48.000
And 71 I was released in New Jersey.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:55.000
And then I came back and went back to work at the State Archives.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:57:01.000
And so you sort of migrated back to a certain extent to America's.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:11.000
Because now you're spearheading this effort to keep the America's movement alive on the minds and in the memories of people.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:14.000
That is correct.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:24.000
And 2007, myself and several other veterans of the Americas movement decided to convene on America's once again to.

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:37.000
Because one of the things we recognize as movement veterans is that a lot of us hadn't passed on these stories to our kids.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:43.000
And we don't have no idea what some of the parents had been through.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:51.000
A lot of the history had been lost, a lot of these significant things that we talked about in terms of the Americas for.

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:56.000
And the women who were arrested for trying to vote.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:07.000
All of this was going to be lost if we didn't take up the mantle and try to collect this information and put it out there.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:11.000
So we met in America's in 2007.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:17.000
We met at a place which was around zero.

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:20.000
A place called Bottoms funeral home.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:27.000
It was one of the places where we would feel a director who and his whole family had allowed us to use this place for a meeting place.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:31.000
He was the sole bail bondsman for the Americas movement.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:35.000
People got arrested. He was the only bondsman who could bail for us.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:45.000
We went back there and met his daughter who was also incarcerated at Leesburg, who's now the director of the funeral home there.

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:48.000
She allowed us to come there and be back once again.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:53.000
And we decided that every two years we would want to have a tribute.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:59:05.000
But in a long range ago it was to somehow either bill or constitute a museum there, but the housing materials that we had begun to collect.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:12.000
And we were all about the business of collecting photographs, some of us had kept things from that time.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:21.000
Flyers, we had formed a newsletter among the simmers at that time.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.000
And we published a newsletter out of the SNCC House with an old memory graph machine.

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:28.000
It was called the Voice of Americus in Southwest Georgia.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:38.000
It was a six page mimeograph that, and we assigned people as reporters, you know, we have people going to other counties here reporting on what happened in this county.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:44.000
We have copies of those (Voice of Americus issues) that we kept in our archives.

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:52.000
And so that was a long range mission.

00:59:52.000 --> 01:00:03.000
The other niches we had to do with trying to provide scholarships for kids who were doing things today in that community service things in that community.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:14.000
We have started a mentoring program of kids trying to get adults to mentor kids who we see falling through the cracks, you know.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:18.000
That mission has led us a lot of different paths.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:27.000
We are connecting with the grandkids of some of the veterans of the movement who had no idea that that parents were involved.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:39.000
Fascinating thing is that each celebration we bring out the photographs and we went through all the newspapers that covered the Americus Movement.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:43.000
(Americus) Times-Recorder literally did no reporting because it didn't work to get out.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:50.000
But papers like Atlanta Journal, Columbus Ledger-Enquirer-Enquirer, Macon Telegraph, Atlanta Daily World.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:58.000
We come through their archives and we reproduce photographs, I mean, the news articles, photographs.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:06.000
And we, it's a very kind of a crew display because we just blew it up with what we had.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Xerox machine, at some point we want to get these things digitized and then they can have better presentation.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:18.000
But we have these four by six frame pieces that we display every celebration.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:26.000
And on one occasion we had a young lady walk through the, and she was looking at the photographs.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:30.000
She saw a picture of a woman who was pregnant.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:34.000
And she said, that's my mother.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:38.000
Okay, and that's me and her belly.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:45.000
So her mother had not told her what she had done.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:55.000
And she just literally went well at that time because she had no idea that her mother was one of those foot soldiers at that time.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:02.000
So it's those things like that that propels you even more to know that the work you're doing is important.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:08.000
We are committed to, to, to, to, to send this project to, to fruition.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:14.000
We're trying to make some connections with the local university there who want to help us with our oral history project.

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:21.000
And hopefully other things will come as a result, as also as well.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:27.000
This happens to be Jimmy Carter of Alma Mater as well in America, sir.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:35.000
So it's not just about, it is about, very much about remembering the movement, but it's also about keeping the spirit of the movement.

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:36.000
Exactly.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:37.000
A lot.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:38.000
Exactly.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:54.000
It's, we want to, in fact, the whole idea of the scholarship is to nurture a whole new generation of young activists to get them to see that they stand on the shoulders of some people who just made some tremendous miscyclophages.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:03:04.000
And we want them to know that, that, that this work has to go on and it won't only go on if they take initiative and, and take the lead.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:07.000
And, because of the times we pass to them.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:13.000
And so we, we expect them to do it, you know.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:16.000
It's expected of them to do that.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:21.000
And so that's, that's been our mission. Every, every two years we, we do that.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Sam Mahon, thank you very much.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:25.000
Thank you.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:26.000
Appreciate it.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:27.000
Thank you.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:28.000
Thank you.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:29.000
Thank you.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:30.000
Thank you.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:31.000
Thank you.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:39.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

